{
  "patent_claims": [
    {
      "claim_number": "1",
      "text": "A system for single-molecule tracking comprising: a processor; a memory storing instructions executable by the processor; a plurality of imaging modalities configured to acquire sequential fluorescence microscopy data of labeled biomolecules; a graph neural network (GNN) module operatively coupled to the processor and configured to receive as input a dynamic graph representation of molecular trajectories derived from the sequential fluorescence microscopy data, wherein the dynamic graph representation comprises nodes corresponding to localized molecular positions and edges representing spatial and temporal adjacency relationships between successive localizations; a trajectory prediction engine integrated with the GNN module and configured to generate predicted molecular trajectories by iteratively updating node embeddings within the dynamic graph using learned message-passing functions; and an output module configured to render visualized tracking results on a display device, wherein the rendered results include annotated molecular paths with associated confidence metrics derived from uncertainty-aware prediction outputs of the GNN module."
    },
    {
      "claim_number": "2",
      "text": "The system of claim 1, wherein the graph neural network module is configured to process node features comprising molecular intensity, localization precision, and temporal displacement vectors, and wherein edge attributes include inter-molecular distance estimates and temporal coherence scores."
    },
    {
      "claim_number": "3",
      "text": "The system of claim 1, wherein the trajectory prediction engine employs a recurrent graph attention mechanism to model long-range dependencies across frames, and wherein the message-passing functions incorporate edge-conditioned convolution operations to aggregate contextual information from neighboring nodes."
    },
    {
      "claim_number": "4",
      "text": "The system of claim 1, wherein the system is configured to operate in real-time with a latency of less than 50 milliseconds from image acquisition to trajectory output, and wherein the processor is further configured to dynamically adjust graph connectivity based on adaptive thresholding of spatial proximity and temporal consistency."
    },
    {
      "claim_number": "5",
      "text": "The system of claim 1, wherein the imaging modalities include at least one of: single-molecule localization microscopy (SMLM), stochastic optical reconstruction microscopy (STORM), or DNA-PAINT, and wherein the preprocessing pipeline performs drift correction and background subtraction prior to graph construction."
    },
    {
      "claim_number": "6",
      "text": "The system of claim 1, wherein the GNN module is trained using a supervised learning framework on a dataset of ground-truth synthetic molecular trajectories generated from simulated diffusion processes with known ground-truth connectivity, and wherein the loss function comprises a composite term including a trajectory consistency loss, a spatial accuracy loss, and a temporal smoothness regularization term."
    },
    {
      "claim_number": "7",
      "text": "The system of claim 1, wherein the output module is further configured to interface with downstream analysis tools for co-localization detection, binding-event inference, and single-molecule interaction mapping in live-cell imaging applications."
    },
    {
      "claim_number": "8",
      "text": "A method for single-molecule tracking using a graph neural network, the method comprising: acquiring, by a computing device, sequential fluorescence microscopy data from labeled biomolecules across multiple imaging planes; constructing, by the computing device, a dynamic graph for each time frame wherein nodes represent localized molecular positions and edges represent spatial-temporal adjacency relationships between successive localizations; inputting, by the computing device, the dynamic graph into a trained graph neural network configured to perform message passing over node and edge features; updating, by the computing device, node embeddings through iterative message-passing operations to predict future positions of tracked molecules; generating, by the computing device, predicted molecular trajectories based on the updated embeddings; and rendering, by the computing device, visualized tracking outputs on a graphical display with uncertainty bounds derived from predictive variance."
    },
    {
      "claim_number": "9",
      "text": "The method of claim 8, wherein the graph neural network is configured to output per-node uncertainty estimates, and wherein the rendering step includes color-coding or halo effects to visually represent confidence levels associated with each predicted trajectory."
    },
    {
      "claim_number": "10",
      "text": "The method of claim 8, wherein the dynamic graph is constructed using a variable node degree scheme that accommodates variable blinking rates and photobleaching events observed in single-molecule datasets."
    },
    {
      "claim_number": "11",
      "text": "The method of claim 8, wherein the training of the graph neural network utilizes experimental ground-truth data acquired from dual-color coincidence imaging to validate tracking accuracy under crowded cellular environments."
    },
    {
      "claim_number": "12",
      "text": "A non-transitory computer-readable storage medium storing instructions that, when executed by a processor, cause the processor to perform a method for single-molecule tracking using graph neural networks, the method comprising: acquiring sequential fluorescence microscopy data; constructing dynamic graphs representing molecular localizations and their spatiotemporal relationships; processing the dynamic graphs through a graph neural network to predict molecular trajectories; generating output trajectories with associated uncertainty metrics; and rendering the trajectories on a display with visual annotations indicating tracking reliability."
    }
  ],
  "specification": {
    "abstract": "

